05718nmm a2200625Ia 9781478059318DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780593187 a10.1515/97814780593182doi  a(DE-B1597)685447  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aPorous Becomings :bAnthropological Engagements with Michel Serres /ced. by Daniel M. Knight, Andreas Bandak. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tANGEL HAIR ANTHROPOLOGY WITH MICHEL SERRES -- tPART I. OF PARASITES AND CONTRACTS -- t1 Three Tales on the Arts of Entrapment: Natural Contracts, Melodic Contaminations, and Spiderweb Anthropologies -- t2 Under the Sign of Hermes: Transgression, the Trickster, and Natural Justice -- t3 Keeping to Oneself: Hospitality and the Magical Hoard in the Balga of Jordan -- tChapter 3 Postscript: Connective Tissue -- t4 Serres, the Sea, the Human, and Anthropology -- tPART II. BODIES IN TIME -- t5 Variations of Bodies in Motion and Relation -- t6 When War Percolates: On Topologies of Earthly Violence in a Planetary Age -- t7 Feeling Safe in a Panbiotic World -- t8 Michel Serres and Gregory Bateson: Implicit Dialogue about a Recognitive Epistemology of Nature -- tPART III. KNOWLEDGE QUESTS -- t9 Angelology -- t10 Forms of Proximity -- t11 Comedic Transubstantiation: The Hermesian Paradox of Being Funny among Stand-Up Comics in New York City -- t12 Michel Serres, Wisdom, Anthropology -- tAfterword: Conversations with Jane Bennett -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the foremost intellectuals of his generation, French philosopher of science Michel Serres (1930–2019) broke free from disciplinary dogmas. His reflections on science, culture, technology, art, and religion have proved foundational to scholars across the humanities. The contributors to Porous Becomings bring the inspirational and enigmatic world of Serres to the attention of anthropology. Through ethnographic encounters as diverse as angels and religious conversion in Ethiopia, the percolation of war in Bosnia, and incarcerated bodies crossing the Atlantic, the contributors showcase how Serres’s interrogation of the fundamentals of human existence opens new pathways for anthropological knowledge. Proposing the notion of "porosity" to characterize permeability across boundaries of time, space, literary genre, and academic discipline, they draw on Serres to map the constellations that connect humans, time, technology, and planet Earth. The volume concludes with a conversation between the editors and Vibrant Matter author Jane Bennett.Contributors. Andreas Bandak, Jane Bennett, Tom Boylston, Steven D. Brown, Matei Candea, Alberto Corsín Jiménez, David Henig, Michael Jackson, Daniel M. Knight, Celia Lowe, Morten Nielsen, Stavroula Pipyrou, Elizabeth Povinelli, Andrew Shryock, Arpad Szakolczai  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBandak, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBandak, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBennett, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoylston, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Steven D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandea, Matei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorsín Jiménez, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo